Interface SetInterface<E>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public interface SetInterface<E>
extends java.io.Serializable
    Set is an interface that describes the operations of the ADT set. A set is a homogeneous collection of objects. It is unordered, there are no limits on the number of items it can store, and it cannot contain duplicate items.

      • add

        boolean add(E newEntry)
     throws SetFullException,
            java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Adds a new entry to this set, avoiding duplicates.

        If newEntry is not null, this set does not contain newEntry, and this set has available capacity (if fixed), then add modifies the set so that it contains newEntry. All other entries remain unmodified. Duplicates are determined using the .equals() method.

        If newEntry is null, then add throws IllegalArgumentException without modifying the set. If this set already contains newEntry, then add returns false without modifying the set. If this set has a capacity limit, and does not have available capacity, then add throws SetFullException without modifying the set.

        Parameters:
        newEntry - The object to be added as a new entry
        Returns:
        true if the addition is successful; false if the item already is in this set
        Throws:
        SetFullException - If this set has a fixed capacity and does not have the capacity to store an additional entry
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If newEntry is null

      • remove

        boolean remove(E entry)
        throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Removes a specific entry from this set, if possible.

        If this set contains the entry, remove will modify the set so that it no longer contains entry. All other entries remain unmodified. Locating this entry is accomplished using the .equals() method.

        If this set does not contain entry, remove will return false without modifying the set. If entry is null, then remove throws IllegalArgumentException without modifying the set.

        Parameters:
        entry - The entry to be removed
        Returns:
        true if the removal was successful; false if not
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If entry is null

      • remove

        E remove()
        Removes an arbitrary entry from this set, if possible.

        If this set contains at least one entry, remove will modify the set so that it no longer contains one of its entries. All other entries remain unmodified. The removed entry will be returned.

        If this set is empty, remove will return null without modifying the set. Because null cannot be added, a return value of null will never indicate a successful removal.

        Returns:
        The removed entry if the removal was successful; null otherwise

      • clear

        void clear()
        Removes all entries from this set.

        If this set is already empty, clear will not modify the set. Otherwise, the set will be modified so that it contains no entries.

      • contains

        boolean contains(E entry)
          throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Tests whether this set contains a given entry. Equality is determined using the .equals() method.

        If this set contains entry, then contains returns true. Otherwise (including if this set is empty), contains returns false. If entry is null, then remove throws IllegalArgumentException. The method never modifies this set.

        Parameters:
        entry - The entry to locate
        Returns:
        true if this set contains entry; false if not
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If entry is null

      • toArray

        E[] toArray()
        Retrieves all entries that are in this set.

        An array is returned that contains a reference to each of the entries in this set. The returned array's length will be equal to the number of elements in this set, and thus the array will contain no null values.

        If the implementation of set is array-backed, toArray will not return the private backing array. Instead, a new array will be allocated with the appropriate capacity.

        Returns:
        A newly-allocated array of all the entries in this set
